%[text] # R03: Forensic Chemometrics -- Multiclass Classification and Parallel Screening
%[text] EasyMolKit Research -- Layer 4
%[text] 
%[text] Can we categorize unknown powders seized in a warehouse using only structural information?
%[text] By compressing ECFP4 fingerprints into 15 dimensions using Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and applying Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), we can determine "drug, analgesic, stimulant, flavor, solvent" with posterior probabilities.
%[text] In this script, we build a pipeline using a forensic reference database of 55 compounds and actually classify 5 simulated seized samples.
%[text] 
%[text] ## Story
%[text] Suppose you receive 5 unlabeled powder samples seized from a warehouse during a drug investigation. Each sample is analyzed by GC-MS, and the molecular structures are decoded as SMILES strings. Visual inspection confirms structural diversity, with some resembling drug-like compounds and others similar to flavor compounds.
%[text] As a chemical investigation team, you need to answer the following three questions:
%[text] - To which chemical category does each sample belong? (drug / analgesic / stimulant / flavor / solvent / food\_acid / sugar / vitamin / other)
%[text] - What is the probability that each sample is a pharmaceutical?
%[text] - What is the closest structural match in the reference database, and what is the confidence level of that assignment? \
%[text] ## Learning Objectives
%[text] 1. Calculate ECFP4 fingerprints for a forensic reference database of 55 compounds and visualize the chemical space using PCA.
%[text] 2. Train an LDA classifier (`fitcdiscr`) for multiclass prediction.
%[text] 3. Evaluate the classifier's reliability using leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV) and interpret the confusion matrix.
%[text] 4. Benchmark parfor and serial loops in batch fingerprinting of 200 FDA drugs to understand conditions where parallel processing speeds up.
%[text] 5. Classify 5 unknown samples using LDA + nearest neighbor similarity and integrate both pieces of evidence.
%[text] 6. Generate a structured forensic classification report. \
%[text] ## Prerequisites
%[text] - Completion of S05 (Unknown Substance Identification) -- Fingerprint Search
%[text] - Completion of A04 (Drug Classification) -- Fingerprint PCA + SVM
%[text] - Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox (`fitcdiscr`, `cvpartition`, `confusionchart`)
%[text] - Parallel Computing Toolbox (`parfor`, `gcp`) -- If not installed, `parfor` automatically falls back to serial `for` loops and displays equivalent results \
%[text] ## Operating Environment
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Environment | Operation |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | MATLAB Desktop (Multicore CPU + PCT) | Full parfor acceleration |
%[text] | MATLAB Desktop (No PCT) | Serial for loop fallback (automatic) |
%[text] | MATLAB Online (Campus-Wide) | Serial fallback (PCT not available on Free Tier) |
%[text:table]
%[text] Reference: mathworks.com/products/matlab-online/limitations.html
%[text] ## Data
%[text] - `data/list/forensic_challenge.csv` -- Forensic reference DB of 55 compounds
%[text] - `data/list/fda_drugs.csv` -- 200 FDA-approved drugs (for parallel demo)
%[text] - Columns: ID, Name, SMILES, is\_drug, ChEMBLID, Category, Source
%[text] - License: ChEMBL CC-BY-SA 3.0 / PubChem CC0 \
%[text] ## References
%[text] - Fisher RA (1936) The use of multiple measurements in taxonomic problems. Ann Eugenics 7:179-188. doi:10.1111/j.1469-1809.1936.tb02137.x \[Origin of LDA / Fisher's Linear Discriminant\]
%[text] - Rogers D & Hahn M (2010) Extended-connectivity fingerprints. J Chem Inf Model 50:742-754. doi:10.1021/ci100050t \[ECFP4 Fingerprint Algorithm\]
%[text] - Varmuza K & Filzmoser P (2009) Introduction to Multivariate Statistical Analysis in Chemometrics. CRC Press. ISBN 978-1420059465. \[Overview of Chemometrics: PCA, LDA, Validation\]
%[text] - Brown SD, Tauler R & Walczak B (eds) (2009) Comprehensive Chemometrics. Elsevier. ISBN 978-0444527028. \[Reference for Forensic Chemometrics Applications\]
%[text] - Lavine BK & Workman J (2008) Chemometrics. Anal Chem 80:4519-4531. doi:10.1021/ac800473d \[Review of Chemometrics Methods in Analytical Chemistry\]
%[text] - Brereton RG (2003) Chemometrics: Data Analysis for the Laboratory and Chemical Plant. John Wiley & Sons. doi:10.1002/0470863242 \[LDA, Cross-Validation, Confusion Matrix in Analytical Context\] \
%[text] 
%[text] Estimated Time: 45-90 minutes | Execution: Run each section with Ctrl+Enter
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif isfolder(fullfile(pwd, 'src'))
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(pwd, 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:777e888a]
%[text] Warm up the Python/RDKit process before main execution.
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane -- lightweight molecule
clear mol_warmup;
%[text] Check for the presence of the Parallel Computing Toolbox.
hasPCT = license("test", "distrib_computing_toolbox");
if hasPCT %[output:group:9385ea20]
    logInfo("R03: Parallel Computing Toolbox detected."); %[output:3fde1728]
    try
        pool = gcp("nocreate");
        if isempty(pool)
            % MATLAB Online supports only the "Threads" profile;
            % Use "Processes" for true multi-process parallelism on Desktop.
            if emk.util.isOnline()
                pool = parpool("Threads", min(4, feature("numcores")));
            else
                pool = parpool("Processes", min(4, feature("numcores"))); %[output:6c2a99dd]
            end
            logInfo("R03: Parallel pool started with %d workers.", pool.NumWorkers); %[output:5f10ad13]
        else
            logInfo("R03: Using existing parallel pool (%d workers).", pool.NumWorkers);
        end
    catch ex
        logWarn("R03: Failed to start parallel pool: %s", ex.message);
        logWarn("     Section 4 will run with serial fallback.");
        hasPCT = false;
    end
else
    logWarn("R03: Parallel Computing Toolbox not detected.");
    logWarn("     Section 4 will use a serial for loop (results are identical).");
end %[output:group:9385ea20]
logInfo("R03: Setup complete."); %[output:2a7fc8e4]
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Loading Forensic Reference Database and Fingerprint Calculation
%[text] In chemometrics, each molecule is represented as a point in a high-dimensional feature space. The 2048-bit ECFP4 fingerprint places each molecule in a 2048-dimensional Boolean space, where each bit $b(j) \\in \\{0, 1\\}$ signals the presence of a substructure identified by the Morgan algorithm (radius 2).
%[text] The forensic reference database contains 55 compounds across 9 chemical categories, assigned labels as follows:
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Field Value | Assigned Label | Origin |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | is\_drug = 1 | drug | Pharmaceuticals (ChEMBL) |
%[text] | is\_drug = 0 | Use Category field as is | Everyday chemicals (PubChem) |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] Workflow to obtain the fingerprint matrix $X$ (size $55 \\times 2048$) from SMILES.
%[text]     \[55 SMILES\]
%[text]          |  (RDKit ECFP4)
%[text]          v
%[text]     \[55 x 2048 Binary Matrix\]   \<-- High-dimensional feature space
%[text]          |  (PCA, 15 components)
%[text]          v
%[text]     \[55 x 15 Score Matrix\]       \<-- Reduced chemical space
%[text]          |  (LDA)
%[text]          v
%[text]     \[Multiclass Classifier\]            \<-- Forensic Category Predictor
%[text] 
%[text] In MATLAB, `emk.fingerprint.morgan()` computes the RDKit Morgan fingerprint, and `emk.fingerprint.toArray()` converts it to a `logical` row vector. The matrix formed by stacking these vertically is `bitMat`, which serves as input for subsequent PCA and LDA.
FP_RADIUS = 2;
FP_NBITS  = 2048;
FC_FILE   = "data/list/forensic_challenge.csv";
fcTbl = readtable(FC_FILE, TextType="string");
logInfo("Forensic DB: Loaded %d compounds from %s.", height(fcTbl), FC_FILE); %[output:1ac8c354]
%[text] Assign integrated category labels based on the `is_drug` field.
n = height(fcTbl);
catLabels = strings(n, 1);
for k = 1:n
    if fcTbl.is_drug(k) == 1
        catLabels(k) = "drug";
    else
        cat = strtrim(lower(fcTbl.Category(k)));
        if cat == "" || cat == "0" || ismissing(cat)
            catLabels(k) = "other";
        else
            catLabels(k) = cat;
        end
    end
end
%[text] Calculate ECFP4 fingerprints for all reference compounds.
fps  = cell(1, n);
mols = cell(1, n);
valid = false(1, n);
for k = 1:n %[output:group:3ab8f08e]
    try
        mols{k}  = emk.mol.fromSmiles(fcTbl.SMILES(k));
        fps{k}   = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mols{k}, Radius=FP_RADIUS, NBits=FP_NBITS);
        valid(k) = true;
    catch
        logWarn("R03: Could not parse %s (%s) -- skipping", ...
            fcTbl.Name(k), fcTbl.SMILES(k));
    end
    if mod(k, max(1, round(n/10))) == 0 || k == n
        logProgress(k, n, "Reference DB Fingerprint Calculation"); %[output:51b4ed62]
    end
end %[output:group:3ab8f08e]
validIdx  = find(valid);
fps       = fps(validIdx);
mols      = mols(validIdx);
names     = fcTbl.Name(validIdx);
smiles    = fcTbl.SMILES(validIdx);
catLabels = catLabels(validIdx);
isDrug    = fcTbl.is_drug(validIdx);
nRef      = numel(validIdx);
%[text] Convert each fingerprint to a `logical` row vector using `emk.fingerprint.toArray()` and assemble the bit matrix `bitMat`.
bitMat = false(nRef, FP_NBITS);
for j = 1:nRef
    bitMat(j, :) = emk.fingerprint.toArray(fps{j});
end
logInfo("Parsed %d / %d reference compounds.", nRef, n); %[output:8e6398a9]
logInfo("Category breakdown:"); %[output:11ad3e44]
cats = unique(catLabels);
for c = 1:numel(cats) %[output:group:0fc622c6]
    cnt = sum(catLabels == cats(c));
    logInfo("  %-12s : %d", cats(c), cnt); %[output:39eed182]
end %[output:group:0fc622c6]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: PCA -- Visualization of Forensic Chemical Space
%[text] Principal Component Analysis (PCA) finds orthogonal directions of maximum variance, one at a time. We apply it here to the binary fingerprint matrix $X$ ($55 \\times 2048$).
%[text] 
%[text] **Step 1: Centering**
%[text] Subtract the column mean $\\mu(j)$ from each bit column to obtain the centered matrix $\\tilde{X}$: $\\tilde{X}(i,j) = X(i,j) - \\mu(j)$.
%[text] In MATLAB: `bitMat_c = double(bitMat) - bitMean`, where `bitMean` is the column mean vector.
%[text] 
%[text] **Step 2: Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)**
%[text] Decompose $\\tilde{X} = U S V^T$, where each column of $V$ is a principal component direction (loading vector).
%[text] MATLAB's `pca()` performs this internally and returns the score matrix $T = \\tilde{X} V(1:k)$.
%[text] 
%[text] **Step 3: Explained Variance**
%[text] The explained variance of PC $i$ is $\\lambda(i) / \\sum\_j \\lambda(j) \\times 100\\,\\%$, where $\\lambda(i) = S(i,i)^2 / (n-1)$ is the eigenvalue.
%[text] MATLAB's `pca()` returns this directly as its fifth output (`explained`). Inspect a scree plot to select $k$.
%[text] 
%[text] **Why PCA Before LDA?**
%[text] With 2048 features and only 55 samples ($p \\gg n$), the within-class scatter matrix $S\_w$ of LDA is singular -- its inverse does not exist.
%[text] Reducing to $k \< n$ dimensions with PCA makes $S\_w$ full-rank and enables the LDA computation.
%[text] 
%[text] We choose $k = 15$ because the scree plot shows the first 15 PCs capturing about 58% of the variance, with a gradual decline thereafter. For 55 structurally diverse compounds, variance spreads across many components, and 58% cumulative explained variance gives the LDA enough signal to operate stably.
N_PCS = 15;
%[text] Save `bitMean` in a separate variable for later centering of test samples.
bitMean  = mean(double(bitMat), 1);
bitMat_c = double(bitMat) - bitMean;
pca_ws = warning("off", "stats:pca:ColRankDefX");
[pcCoeff, pcScore, ~, ~, explained] = pca(bitMat_c, NumComponents=N_PCS);
warning(pca_ws);
logInfo("PCA: Top %d PCs explain %.1f%% of fingerprint variance.", ... %[output:group:45e4655a] %[output:3e4c4dfb]
    N_PCS, sum(explained(1:N_PCS))); %[output:group:45e4655a] %[output:3e4c4dfb]
%[text] \--- Figure 1: Scree Plot (Individual and Cumulative Explained Variance) ---
%[text] The bar graph shows individual %, and the line shows cumulative %. The dashed line $k = 15$ is the cutoff.
figure("Name", "R03 Fig 1: PCA Scree Plot"); %[output:59f54cde]
bar(1:min(30, numel(explained)), explained(1:min(30, numel(explained))), ... %[output:59f54cde]
    FaceColor=[0.4 0.6 0.8]); %[output:59f54cde]
hold on; %[output:59f54cde]
plot(1:min(30, numel(explained)), cumsum(explained(1:min(30, numel(explained)))), ... %[output:59f54cde]
    "-ro", MarkerSize=5, LineWidth=1.5, DisplayName="Cumulative %"); %[output:59f54cde]
hold off; %[output:59f54cde]
xline(N_PCS, "--k", sprintf("k=%d", N_PCS), LabelVerticalAlignment="bottom"); %[output:59f54cde]
xlabel("Principal Component"); %[output:59f54cde]
ylabel("Explained Variance (%)"); %[output:59f54cde]
title("Scree Plot -- ECFP4 Forensic DB"); %[output:59f54cde]
legend(["Individual %", "Cumulative %"], Location="northeast"); %[output:59f54cde]
grid on; %[output:59f54cde]
%[text] \--- Figure 2: PC1 vs PC2 Colored by Category ---
%[text] PC1 and PC2 capture the two largest sources of variance, revealing the most prominent structural contrasts in this chemical space.
%[text] Notice how structurally similar compounds cluster together while chemically distinct categories separate.
catUniq   = unique(catLabels);
nCats     = numel(catUniq);
cmap      = lines(nCats);
markerMap = containers.Map( ...
    {'drug','analgesic','stimulant','flavor','solvent','sugar','food_acid','other','vitamin'}, ...
    {'o',    '^',        's',        'd',     'v',      'p',    'h',        'x',   '*'});
figure("Name", "R03 Fig 2: Chemical Space PCA"); %[output:091bc521]
hold on; %[output:091bc521]
for c = 1:nCats
    idx = catLabels == catUniq(c);
    mk  = "o";
    if isKey(markerMap, char(catUniq(c))); mk = markerMap(char(catUniq(c))); end
    scatter(pcScore(idx, 1), pcScore(idx, 2), 60, cmap(c, :), mk, ... %[output:091bc521]
        "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.75, DisplayName=catUniq(c)); %[output:091bc521]
end
hold off; %[output:091bc521]
xlabel(sprintf("PC1 (%.1f%%)", explained(1))); %[output:091bc521]
ylabel(sprintf("PC2 (%.1f%%)", explained(2))); %[output:091bc521]
title("Forensic Reference DB -- PC1 vs PC2 (ECFP4)"); %[output:091bc521]
legend(Location="best", FontSize=8, Interpreter="none"); %[output:091bc521]
grid on; %[output:091bc521]
logInfo("R03: PCA visualization complete."); %[output:5a616070]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: LDA Classifier -- Multiclass Forensic Category Prediction
%[text] Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) finds a linear combination of features that maximally separates classes.
%[text] Given the within-class scatter matrix $S\_w$ and between-class scatter matrix $S\_b$, LDA seeks the direction $w$ that maximizes the Fisher criterion $J(w) = \\frac{w^T S\_b w}{w^T S\_w w}$ (Fisher, 1936).
%[text] Maximizing $J(w)$ reduces to the generalized eigenvalue problem $S\_b w = \\lambda S\_w w$, which yields up to $C - 1$ discriminant directions for a $C$-class problem. Here with 9 categories, that means up to 8 directions.
%[text] 
%[text] MATLAB's `fitcdiscr(X, y, DiscrimType="linear")` handles this internally, using a pseudo-inverse fallback when $S\_w$ is nearly singular.
%[text] With 15 PCA scores and 55 samples, the matrix is well-conditioned, so this fallback is not needed.
%[text] 
%[text] **Posterior Probabilities**
%[text] The `score` matrix ($N \\times C$) from `predict()` holds class posterior probabilities $P(c \\mid x)$, not LDA discriminant coordinates. These are computed via Bayes' rule $P(c \\mid x) \\propto{}P(x \\mid c) \\cdot P(c)$ under a Gaussian class-conditional assumption. The column $P(\\text{drug} \\mid x)$ quantifies how drug-like each molecule is.
%[text] 
%[text] **LOOCV: Role and Limitations**
%[text] Leave-one-out cross-validation withholds one sample at a time, giving an unbiased performance estimate. With only $n = 55$ samples, however, variance is high -- a single misclassification shifts accuracy by ~2%. Treat the LOOCV result as a reference, not a precise performance guarantee.
%[text] 
%[text] Use PCA scores (`pcScore`, $55 \\times 15$) as input to LDA.
X = pcScore;            % 55 x 15 PC score matrix
y = catLabels;          % Category label string array
%[text] Fit LDA on the entire dataset (for visualization and deployment).
ldaMdl = fitcdiscr(X, y, DiscrimType="linear");
%[text] Predict on training data (resubstitution). Resubstitution accuracy is an upper bound and optimistic, so always use LOOCV for unbiased estimation.
[yPred_train, posteriors_train, ~] = predict(ldaMdl, X);
trainAcc = mean(yPred_train == y) * 100;
logInfo("LDA Training Accuracy (Resubstitution): %.1f%% ※This is an optimistic value.", trainAcc); %[output:1ebefcec]
%[text] Estimate unbiased performance with leave-one-out cross-validation.
rng(42);
%[text] Warnings about zero weights for singleton classes (other, vitamin: n=1) are expected.
ws = warning("off", "all");
cvMdl = crossval(ldaMdl, LeaveOut="on");
%[text] `kfoldPredict` returns a cell array of char vectors, so convert to a string array.
yPred_loo = string(kfoldPredict(cvMdl));
warning(ws);
looAcc = mean(yPred_loo == y) * 100;
logInfo("LDA LOOCV Accuracy (leave-one-out): %.1f%%", looAcc); %[output:6031d76a]
%[text] Check LOOCV accuracy by category.
for c = 1:nCats %[output:group:80a10dee]
    idx     = y == catUniq(c);
    catAcc  = mean(yPred_loo(idx) == y(idx)) * 100;
    logInfo("  %-12s  LOOCV Accuracy: %.1f%%  (n=%d)", catUniq(c), catAcc, sum(idx)); %[output:807fabf7]
end %[output:group:80a10dee]
%[text] \--- Figure 3: LOOCV Confusion Matrix (Row Normalized) ---
%[text] Rows represent true categories and columns predicted categories; row normalization lets you read recall directly for each class.
%[text] Replace underscores in labels with hyphens to prevent TeX subscript rendering.
y_disp        = strrep(y,        "_", "-");
yPred_loo_disp = strrep(yPred_loo, "_", "-");
figure("Name", "R03 Fig 3: LDA LOOCV Confusion Matrix"); %[output:7e324bea]
cm = confusionchart(y_disp, yPred_loo_disp, ... %[output:7e324bea]
    Title=sprintf("LDA LOOCV Confusion Matrix (Accuracy = %.1f%%)", looAcc), ... %[output:7e324bea]
    RowSummary="row-normalized", ... %[output:7e324bea]
    ColumnSummary="column-normalized"); %[output:7e324bea]
cm.Normalization = "row-normalized"; %[output:7e324bea]
%[text] \--- Figure 4: P(drug) Posterior Probability by True Category ---
%[text] Each point is $P(\\text{drug} \\mid \\text{ECFP4})$ for a reference compound, grouped by its true category.
%[text] 
%[text] How to read this plot:
%[text] - High $P(\\text{drug})$, true category = drug: model correctly captures drug space.
%[text] - Low $P(\\text{drug})$, true category $\\neq$ drug: model correctly rejects non-drugs.
%[text] - High $P(\\text{drug})$, true category $\\neq$ drug: structurally drug-like non-drugs (e.g., Caffeine, Nicotine). \
%[text] Note: these posteriors are from resubstitution (training data) and are optimistic; use LOOCV posteriors for an unbiased estimate.
drug_col_fig4 = find(strcmp(string(ldaMdl.ClassNames), "drug"), 1);
pDrugAll      = posteriors_train(:, drug_col_fig4);
figure("Name", "R03 Fig 4: P(drug) Posterior by True Category"); %[output:14e6fa5d]
rng(42);
hold on; %[output:14e6fa5d]
for c = 1:nCats
    idx    = y == catUniq(c);
    jitter = (rand(sum(idx), 1) - 0.5) * 0.30;
    scatter(c + jitter, pDrugAll(idx), 55, cmap(c, :), "filled", ... %[output:14e6fa5d]
        "MarkerFaceAlpha", 0.80, DisplayName=catUniq(c)); %[output:14e6fa5d]
end
hold off; %[output:14e6fa5d]
yline(0.5, "--r", "P=0.5", DisplayName="Decision Boundary", LineWidth=1.5); %[output:14e6fa5d]
xticks(1:nCats); %[output:14e6fa5d]
xticklabels(strrep(catUniq, "_", "-")); %[output:14e6fa5d]
xtickangle(30); %[output:14e6fa5d]
xlabel("True Category"); %[output:14e6fa5d]
ylabel("P(drug | ECFP4)  --  LDA Posterior Probability"); %[output:14e6fa5d]
title("Drug Posterior Probability by True Category (Resubstitution)"); %[output:14e6fa5d]
legend(Location="eastoutside", FontSize=8, Interpreter="none"); %[output:14e6fa5d]
grid on; %[output:14e6fa5d]
logInfo("R03: Training and cross-validation of the LDA classifier completed."); %[output:282b75e0]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Parallel Batch Fingerprinting -- parfor vs Serial
%[text] MATLAB's `parfor` distributes independent loop iterations across worker processes in a parallel pool.
%[text] The theoretical speedup follows $S = (n \\cdot t) / (n \\cdot t / W + T\_{ov})$, where $W$ is the number of workers and $T\_{ov}$ is the overhead for pool startup and data transfer.
%[text] 
%[text] **Constraint: RDKit Fingerprint Processing**
%[text] When each iteration calls Python via MATLAB `pyenv` (out-of-process), inter-process communication (IPC) is the bottleneck.
%[text] Because out-of-process Python runs on a single worker, `parfor` cannot parallelize the Python calls themselves.
%[text] 
%[text] **Important:** **`py.*`** **objects cannot be sent to** **`parfor`** **workers**
%[text] MATLAB serializes data between workers using Java, but `py.*` objects (including RDKit fingerprints) do not support this. As a result, `toArray()` must be called in the main process before any `parfor`. Convert all fingerprints to a `logical` bit matrix first, then parallelize pure MATLAB operations.
%[text] 
%[text] **When** **`parfor`** **helps**
%[text] Pure numerical operations on native MATLAB arrays (`double`, `logical`, etc.) -- descriptor calculations, statistical aggregations -- do benefit from `parfor`. This section times the serial fingerprinting and conversion pipeline. For 200 molecules, expect 5--50 s depending on environment (MATLAB Online: ~5 s; Desktop with Processes pool: ~50 s).
FDA_FILE = "data/list/fda_drugs.csv";
fdaTbl   = readtable(FDA_FILE, TextType="string");
nFda     = height(fdaTbl);
logInfo("FDA drug library: %d entries", nFda); %[output:3641c168]
%[text] Step A: Serial Fingerprinting (Baseline Measurement)
fpsSerial = cell(1, nFda);
validFda  = false(1, nFda);
tic;
for k = 1:nFda
    try
        mol          = emk.mol.fromSmiles(fdaTbl.SMILES(k));
        fpsSerial{k} = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol, Radius=FP_RADIUS, NBits=FP_NBITS);
        validFda(k)  = true;
    catch
        % Skip entries that cannot be parsed
    end
end
tSerial = toc;
logInfo("Serial Fingerprinting: %d / %d successful, %.2f seconds (%.0f mol/second)", ... %[output:group:633b07dc] %[output:0e31c1b5]
    sum(validFda), nFda, tSerial, sum(validFda) / tSerial); %[output:group:633b07dc] %[output:0e31c1b5]
validFdaIdx = find(validFda);
fpsSerial   = fpsSerial(validFdaIdx);
namesFda    = fdaTbl.Name(validFdaIdx);
smilesFda   = fdaTbl.SMILES(validFdaIdx);
nFdaValid   = numel(validFdaIdx);
%[text] Step B: Bit Vector Conversion (Serial)
%[text] Since `py.*` objects cannot be serialized to `parfor` workers, `toArray()` conversion is always performed serially in the main process.
%[text] Pure MATLAB operations on the converted `bitMatFda` (`logical` matrix) can be parallelized with `parfor`.
bitMatFda = false(nFdaValid, FP_NBITS);
tic;
for j = 1:nFdaValid
    bitMatFda(j, :) = emk.fingerprint.toArray(fpsSerial{j});
end
tConvert = toc;
logInfo("Bit Vector Conversion (Serial): Processed %d molecules in %.3f seconds.", ... %[output:group:296526f9] %[output:592bac3b]
    nFdaValid, tConvert); %[output:group:296526f9] %[output:592bac3b]
%[text] Step C: Apply PCA + LDA to FDA Library
%[text] Project FDA drugs into forensic PCA space for classification.
%[text] To apply the same centering as during training, it is important to center using the reference DB mean (`bitMean`) rather than the internal FDA mean.
%[text] This ensures that FDA drugs are projected into the same coordinate system as the reference DB.
fdaMat_c   = double(bitMatFda) - bitMean;   % Center using reference mean
fdaPcScore = fdaMat_c * pcCoeff;            % Project onto reference PCs (15)
fdaPcScore = fdaPcScore(:, 1:N_PCS);
[fdaCatPred, fdaPostProb] = predict(ldaMdl, fdaPcScore);
drugPostFda = fdaPostProb(:, strcmp(ldaMdl.ClassNames, "drug"));
logInfo("LDA classified FDA drugs as 'drug': %d / %d (%.1f%%)", ... %[output:group:17af505f] %[output:59643189]
    sum(fdaCatPred == "drug"), nFdaValid, ... %[output:59643189]
    100 * sum(fdaCatPred == "drug") / nFdaValid); %[output:group:17af505f] %[output:59643189]
logInfo("Mean P(drug) for FDA drugs: %.3f", mean(drugPostFda)); %[output:829712c4]
%[text] \--- Figure 5: LDA Drug Posterior Probability Distribution for 200 FDA Drugs ---
%[text] Shows the results of applying LDA trained on the forensic reference DB to 200 FDA drugs.
%[text] The region where $P(\\text{drug}) \> 0.5$ is considered as drugs.
figure("Name", "R03 Fig 5: LDA Drug Posterior -- FDA Drugs"); %[output:75fedc21]
histogram(drugPostFda, 20, FaceColor=[0.3 0.6 0.9], EdgeColor="white"); %[output:75fedc21]
xline(0.5, "--r", "P(drug)=0.5", LineWidth=1.5); %[output:75fedc21]
xlabel("P(drug | molecule)  --  LDA Posterior Probability"); %[output:75fedc21]
ylabel("Number of FDA Drugs"); %[output:75fedc21]
title({"Posterior Probability of Drug for 200 FDA Drugs", "(LDA Trained on Forensic DB)"}); %[output:75fedc21]
grid on; %[output:75fedc21]
logInfo("R03: Batch fingerprint processing complete."); %[output:002dd333]
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Classification of 5 Unknown Seized Samples
%[text] Forensic classification combines two lines of evidence.
%[text] 
%[text] **Line 1: LDA Classification (Model-based, Category Level)**
%[text] The LDA classifier predicts chemical categories and reports $P(c \\mid \\text{fingerprint})$ calibrated against 55 reference compounds. Its strength is robustness to structural novelty, while its weakness is dependency on training set coverage.
%[text] 
%[text] **Line 2: Nearest Neighbor Similarity (Instance-based, Compound Level)**
%[text] Tanimoto similarity $T$ to the nearest reference compound identifies the best structural match.
%[text] In forensic fingerprint literature, $T \\geq 0.85$ is conventionally considered a "very similar scaffold" (strength: no model assumptions, weakness: depends on DB coverage).
%[text] 
%[text] The two lines are integrated to determine the evidence level.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Condition | Evidence Level | Interpretation |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | LDA and NN agree and $T \\geq 0.85$ | HIGH | Strong evidence |
%[text] | Either LDA or NN meets the condition | MEDIUM | Requires additional confirmation |
%[text] | Both lines disagree or $T \< 0.85$ | LOW | Indeterminate, recommend DB expansion |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] In this exercise, we simulate seized samples using known compounds from the forensic DB, allowing for retrospective validation.
UNKNOWNS = struct( ...
    "id",    {"U001", "U002", "U003", "U004", "U005"}, ...
    "smiles", { ...
        "Cn1cnc2c1c(=O)n(C)c(=O)n2C", ...                  % caffeine
        "CC(C)Cc1ccc(cc1)C(C)C(=O)O", ...                  % ibuprofen
        "CN1CCC[C@H]1c1cccnc1", ...                         % nicotine
        "CC(=O)Nc1ccc(O)cc1", ...                           % acetaminophen (paracetamol)
        "CN(C)CCCN1c2ccccc2CCc2ccccc21"} ...                % imipramine (TCA antidepressant)
);
nUnk = numel(UNKNOWNS);
%[text] For each unknown sample, process in the order of fingerprint calculation → PCA projection → LDA classification → nearest neighbor search → evidence integration.
unkNames      = strings(nUnk, 1);
unkCatPred    = strings(nUnk, 1);
unkDrugPost   = zeros(nUnk, 1);
unkNNname     = strings(nUnk, 1);
unkNNtanimoto = zeros(nUnk, 1);
unkNNcat      = strings(nUnk, 1);
unkEvidence   = strings(nUnk, 1);
for u = 1:nUnk %[output:group:1a850d52]
    uid    = UNKNOWNS(u).id;
    smiles_u = UNKNOWNS(u).smiles;
    try
        mol_u = emk.mol.fromSmiles(smiles_u);
    catch ex
        logWarn("R03: Could not parse unknown sample %s: %s", uid, ex.message);
        continue;
    end
    % Fingerprint calculation
    fp_u  = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol_u, Radius=FP_RADIUS, NBits=FP_NBITS);
    bits_u = single(emk.fingerprint.toArray(fp_u));
    % PCA projection (using reference mean and loadings)
    bits_c = double(bits_u) - bitMean;
    pc_u   = bits_c * pcCoeff;    % 1 x N_PCS
    % LDA classification
    [catPred_u, post_u] = predict(ldaMdl, pc_u(1:N_PCS));
    catPred_u = string(catPred_u);   % predict returns a cell array for single-row input
    drugIdx = strcmp(ldaMdl.ClassNames, "drug");
    drugP   = post_u(drugIdx);
    % Nearest neighbor similarity search in reference DB
    tanimotoScores = zeros(nRef, 1);
    for j = 1:nRef
        tanimotoScores(j) = emk.similarity.tanimoto(fp_u, fps{j});
    end
    [maxT, nnIdx] = max(tanimotoScores);
    nnName    = names(nnIdx);
    nnCat     = catLabels(nnIdx);
    % Determine integrated evidence level
    if maxT >= 0.85 && catPred_u == nnCat
        evidence = "HIGH: LDA+NN agree, T>=0.85";
    elseif maxT >= 0.85 || catPred_u == nnCat
        evidence = "MEDIUM: one source strong";
    else
        evidence = "LOW: sources disagree or T<0.85";
    end
    unkNames(u)      = uid;
    unkCatPred(u)    = catPred_u;
    unkDrugPost(u)   = drugP;
    unkNNname(u)     = nnName;
    unkNNtanimoto(u) = maxT;
    unkNNcat(u)      = nnCat;
    unkEvidence(u)   = evidence;
    logInfo("Unknown %s: LDA=%s (P_drug=%.4f), NN=%s (T=%.3f, Category=%s)  -> %s", ... %[output:8f32b1f9]
        uid, catPred_u, drugP, nnName, maxT, nnCat, evidence); %[output:8f32b1f9]
end %[output:group:1a850d52]
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Forensic Classification Report
%[text] The forensic report clearly describes classification results, sources and reliability of evidence, and limitations of the analysis.
%[text] 
%[text] **Main Limitations of This Chemometrics Approach**
%[text] - The reference DB of 55 compounds is small, and new designer drugs or unusual chemicals may fall outside its coverage.
%[text] - LDA posterior probabilities are calibrated on the training set, and calibration accuracy decreases when the number of samples per class is small ($n \< 5$).
%[text] - ECFP4 captures topology but does not reflect 3D structure, stereochemistry, or isotopic composition.
%[text] - Tanimoto $T \\geq 0.85$ is a conventional threshold and not a legal standard.
%[text] - Definitive forensic identification requires MS/MS confirmation. \
%[text] This report is for educational purposes only. In actual forensic contexts, chemometrics results are used for preliminary classification, and confirmatory analysis is always required.
logInfo("Date and Time: %s", char(datetime("now", "Format", "yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss"))); %[output:7fb3a6dd]
logInfo("Method: ECFP4 + PCA (%d components) + LDA (linear)", N_PCS); %[output:66367cb8]
logInfo("Reference DB: %d compounds (%s)", nRef, FC_FILE); %[output:7428f028]
logInfo("LDA LOOCV Accuracy: %.1f%%", looAcc); %[output:5beedd3a]
%[text] Assemble the results table for downstream analysis.
reportTbl = table(unkNames, unkCatPred, unkDrugPost, ...
    unkNNname, unkNNtanimoto, unkNNcat, unkEvidence, ...
    VariableNames=["SampleID","LDA_Category","P_Drug", ...
    "Nearest_Reference","Tanimoto","NN_Category","Evidence_Level"]);
logInfo("List of Classification Results:"); %[output:05e2162e]
disp(reportTbl); %[output:8b38e992]
%[text] Save the report to the execution directory.
outDir  = makeRunDir("Prefix", "r03_forensic");
writetable(reportTbl, fullfile(outDir, "forensic_report.csv"));
logInfo("R03: Report saved to %s.", outDir); %[output:478c71e8]
%%
%[text] ## Section 7: Summary -- Review of the Chemometrics Workflow
%[text] In this exercise, we demonstrated a standard forensic chemometrics pipeline.
%[text] Let's review the methods applied at each step and their MATLAB implementations.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Step | Method | MATLAB Implementation |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | 1\. Encoding | SMILES → ECFP4 (2048 bits) | `emk.fingerprint.morgan()` + `toArray()` |
%[text] | 2\. Dimensionality Reduction (PCA) | 2048 → 15 Principal Components | `pca(bitMat_c, NumComponents=15)` |
%[text] | 3\. Supervised Classification (LDA) | 9 Categories, up to 8 Discriminant Directions | `fitcdiscr()` + `crossval()` |
%[text] | 4\. Batch Application | Projection and Classification of 200 FDA Drugs | Serial `for` + `predict()` |
%[text] | 5\. Unknown Sample Classification | LDA Posterior Probability + Tanimoto NN | `predict()` + `emk.similarity.tanimoto()` |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] **Key Learning Points**
%[text] 1. In situations where $p \\gg n$ (always true for fingerprint data), dimensionality reduction via PCA is essential before LDA.
%[text] 2. LOOCV accuracy (55 samples, 9 categories, approximately 55-80%) reflects the inherent difficulty of multi-class chemical classification with a small reference database.
%[text] 3. `parfor` accelerates pure MATLAB loops handling native MATLAB arrays, but Python IPC boundaries cannot be avoided with `parfor`. Also, since `py.*` objects cannot be serialized to workers, calling `toArray()` within `parfor` results in a runtime error.
%[text] 4. In forensics, a single evidence source is not definitive. Combining LDA posterior probabilities and Tanimoto NN improves confidence. U001 matches perfectly with CAFFEINE (category: drug) in the reference DB with T=1.000 using the SMILES for caffeine, but LDA predicts stimulant. The mismatch between LDA and NN categories resulted in a MEDIUM determination. This is a typical example of LDA overfitting with small n data, highlighting the importance of dual validation. \
%[text] **Next Steps (Beyond This Exercise)**
%[text] - R04: Protein-Ligand Analysis -- Extend to 3D Binding Classification
%[text] - Expand the reference DB for higher coverage (complete ChEMBL subset)
%[text] - Explore QDA, SVM, Random Forest as alternatives to LDA (see A04)
%[text] - Implement SMARTS-based substructure alerts for regulated substances \
logInfo("R03: Forensic Chemometrics Exercise Completed."); %[output:793c0714]

